content.text:
I now have a complete picture. Here is my detailed review.

---

## CHANGES_REQUESTED

### Summary

The change wraps `dispatchEventFocus` in `useCallback` and adds it to the `useEffect` dependency array, which is the textbook fix for `react-hooks/exhaustive-deps`. However, this introduces a **behavioral change** in a project where the constraint is explicitly **no logic changes -- structure only**.

### Detailed Analysis

#### Original Behavior

```typescript
// BEFORE
const dispatchEventFocus = () => { /* ... */ };

useEffect(() => {
  if (isFocused) {
    dispatchEventFocus();
  }
}, [isFocused]);
```

The original `useEffect` ran **only** when `isFocused` changed (i.e., on screen focus/blur transitions). It intentionally captured a stale closure over `route`, `analytic`, `title`, and `handleAfterDispatch`. While this was technically a lint violation, it was the **intended behavior**: fire analytics once on focus, never re-fire if props change while the screen is focused.

#### New Behavior

```typescript
// AFTER
const dispatchEventFocus = useCallback(() => { /* ... */ }, [
  route?.params?.analytics,
  analytic,
  title,
  handleAfterDispatch,
]);

useEffect(() => {
  if (isFocused) {
    dispatchEventFocus();
  }
}, [isFocused, dispatchEventFocus]);
```

The `useEffect` now re-runs whenever any of the `useCallback` dependencies change **while the screen is focused**. This means:

1. **`route?.params?.analytics`**: React Navigation does NOT guarantee referential stability for `route.params`. When params are set via `navigation.setParams()` or during re-navigation, a new `params` object is created. Even without explicit navigation, some scenarios (deep links, state restoration) can cause new `params` references. The `analytics` sub-object extracted from `params` will therefore be a new reference every time `params` changes, even if the content is identical. This means `useCallback` recreates `dispatchEventFocus` on every such change, causing the effect to re-fire and **duplicate analytics events while the screen is focused**.

2. **`handleAfterDispatch`**: Currently no caller passes this prop. However, the interface declares it as `() => void`. Any future caller passing an inline arrow function (the natural pattern) would cause `useCallback` to see a new reference on every render. Combined with `isFocused === true`, this would fire analytics events on every single render while the screen is visible -- effectively an **analytics event flood**. The fact that no caller uses it today does not eliminate the risk; the API contract now silently requires callers to memoize this callback.

3. **`analytic` and `title`**: These are string primitives in all current call sites (string literals like `'Milhas Aereas'`, `'Shopping'`, `'Cashback na fatura'`, `'Saiba mais'`). String primitives are compared by value, so these are safe today. However, if a caller ever passes a dynamically computed string, the same re-fire risk applies.

#### Severity Assessment

| Dependency | Current Risk | Future Risk |
|---|---|---|
| `route?.params?.analytics` | **MEDIUM** -- depends on whether React Navigation recreates `params` objects during re-renders of focused screens | **HIGH** -- any `setParams` call or navigation event while focused will duplicate analytics |
| `handleAfterDispatch` | None (unused) | **HIGH** -- any non-memoized callback will cause per-render analytics firing |
| `analytic` | None (string literal) | Low |
| `title` | None (string literal) | Low |

#### The `if (isFocused)` Guard Is Insufficient

The `if (isFocused)` check only prevents firing when the screen is not focused. It does NOT prevent repeated firing while the screen IS focused. The original code relied on `isFocused` being the sole dependency, meaning the effect body ran only on `isFocused` transitions (false -> true, true -> false). With the new deps, the effect runs on every `dispatchEventFocus` identity change while `isFocused` remains `true`.

#### The `route?.params?.analytics` Dependency is Particularly Dangerous

Using optional chaining in a dependency array (`route?.params?.analytics`) is problematic. React's dependency comparison uses `Object.is`. If `route.params` is `undefined` on one render and then gets set on the next, `route?.params?.analytics` changes from `undefined` to some value, correctly triggering. But when `analytics` is an object, React Navigation creates new object references on re-render even when the content is identical, leading to unnecessary `useCallback` invalidation.

### Recommendation

The correct fix for this specific case, where the original intent was "fire once on focus", is one of:

**Option A -- Suppress the lint rule with justification (preferred for a no-logic-change migration):**

```typescript
const dispatchEventFocus = () => {
  // ... unchanged
};

useEffect(() => {
  if (isFocused) {
    dispatchEventFocus();
  }
  // eslint-disable-next-line react-hooks/exhaustive-deps
}, [isFocused]);
```

This preserves exact original behavior. The lint suppression is justified because the intent is to capture values at focus-time only.

**Option B -- Use a ref to prevent re-dispatch while focused (preserves both lint compliance and original semantics):**

```typescript
const hasFiredRef = useRef(false);

const dispatchEventFocus = useCallback(() => {
  // ... same body
}, [route?.params?.analytics, analytic, title, handleAfterDispatch]);

useEffect(() => {
  if (isFocused && !hasFiredRef.current) {
    hasFiredRef.current = true;
    dispatchEventFocus();
  }
  if (!isFocused) {
    hasFiredRef.current = false;
  }
}, [isFocused, dispatchEventFocus]);
```

This satisfies the exhaustive-deps rule while guaranteeing the analytics event fires at most once per focus session.

### Verdict

The current change introduces a subtle but real behavioral regression: analytics events can fire more than once per focus session if any of the `useCallback` dependencies are referentially unstable. Given the project constraint of **no logic changes during migration**, this change should be revised to either suppress the lint rule (Option A) or add a guard ref (Option B). Option A is safest for a structural-only migration; Option B is technically superior if the project is willing to add the ref as a "structural" enhancement.
